Avoiding the 8fPIN2A0=8bO1DN0E1introduction of error is a much more modest aim than the 8fPIN2A0=8bO1CN0E1elimination of
error.  We believe, however, that the former is a realistic aim for a software tool whereas
the latter is not. Recognition of the  difference between these two goals leads to a
fundamental difference in one's approach to tool building.

8fPHN2A0+ was originally developed to support the work of a research group
active in the area of the mathematics of (computer) program construction.  The nature
of the group's work was (and is) such that their articles frequently involve substantial
algebraic calculations in advanced areas of mathematics.  The primary tools used by the
group to  carry out their work were (and still are) paper and pencil.

Performing algebraic calculations at a computer terminal and doing them by  hand
with paper and pencil are quite different sorts of activities.  In designing 8fPHN2A0+
we started out from the viewpoint that the latter (using paper and pencil) is much
more reliable than the former (using a computer).  This is quite contrary to prevailing
claims made about formal verification systems and the  like.  One must recognise,
however, that,  for us as human beings,  paper and  pencil is so much 8fPIN2A0:8bOON0E1handier;  the
computer, in comparison, is a very clumsy instrument, and the use of a clumsy or
badly-designed tool will inevitably  introduce errors of its own kind.  

The traditional argument for the use of a computer for algebraic calculations,  that
computers are able to faithfully execute formal manipulation rules, is one that we find
difficult to justify in the context of our own research.  The  problem is that it is
frequently hard to explain to a dumb machine how a rule  should be applied in a
particular situation because there are ---from the  trained scientist's point of view---
so many trivial intermediate steps that also have to be explained.  The icon that is used
